# Athlete Monitoring Prototype - Progress Tracker
This project is a prototype lumbar-mounted athlete monitoring data logger for running fatigue detection, built on an STM32 Nucleo-L476RG with breakout sensors. The current stack is BMI270 IMU (I2C, target 200 Hz accel+gyro with FIFO watermark interrupt batching), BMP390 barometer (I2C, default 0x77 with fallback 0x76, low-rate pressure/elevation trend), and later u-blox MAX-10S GNSS for route context and precise time synchronization across future multi-node devices (for example lumbar + tibia units). Data is being structured now in a fixed, backward-compatible schema with a unified millisecond timestamp and status bitfield so Phase 1 (IMU-first) logs remain compatible when barometer, GNSS, and SD card logging are added. Current priorities are robust sensor initialization, timing discipline, FIFO/interrupt reliability, deterministic logging architecture, and validation tests (noise floor, clipping, drift, overflow, and long-run stability) before moving to post-processing fatigue features like step frequency, peak vertical acceleration, stride regularity, and dynamic stress load.

